DENGUE/DHF UPDATE 2006 (01)
***************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[This is by no means a comprehensive collection of all reports of
dengue in the world since the last update. In order to make it more
inclusive, ProMED-mail asks readers to send reports of dengue
outbreaks that they find to <promed@promedmail.org>.]
In this update:
[1] Indonesia
[2] China (Hong Kong, SAR)
[3] Mexico (Oaxaca)
*****
[1] Indonesia
Date: Wed, 4 Jan 2006 05:16:16 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Jakarta Post, Indonesia, 4 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailnational.asp?fileid=20060104.D10&irec=9>

Dengue fever has become a grave threat for people in Bantul regency,
Yogyakarta, with the number of people contracting the dengue virus
last month [Dec 2005] reaching 61 people, a 300 percent increase
compared to [Nov 2005]. The number is expected to increase in coming
months [as of Jan 2006] as rain has started to pound the region, said
health officer with Bantul regency administration Gandung Bambang Hermanto.
"While in October and November [2005] only 22 and 20 people were
infected with the dengue virus, respectively, in December the number
rose to 61 people," said Gandung, the chief of surveillance section
with Bantul health office.
Besides the rainy season, bad sanitation was also blamed for the
rising number of people contracting the disease, said Gandung. "We
regret that the area free of [_Aedes aegypti_] mosquito larvae in the
regency is only 67 percent of the total area, while in order to be
free of dengue the area free of mosquito larvae should reach 95
percent," said Gandung.
The rainy season has provided ample opportunity for the mosquito to
breed. The rain has created puddles in many areas, making ideal
breeding grounds for [_Aedes aegypti_] mosquitoes, the carrier of
dengue fever, said Gandung.
In order to prevent the spread of the disease, the government has
intensified its campaign by calling on the public to clean up the
environment. The government also distributed larvicidal powder in
order to help destroy mosquito larvae.
"A mosquito can produce 400 larvae in a single go. Can you imagine
how many larvae would persist in a puddle if we do not clean this
up?" said Gandung.
With the additional 61 persons, the number of people contracting
dengue virus in Bantul totaled 195 in 2005. 4 of these people died,
according to Gandung.
Bantul is a regency next to ancient city of Yogyakarta, which has for
years been a popular destination for tourists, both foreign and domestic.
--
